2023 European Athletics Team Championships First Division

The 2023 European Athletics Team Championships First Division was held on 23–25 June 2023 in Chorzów, Poland. This edition marked the first time all divisions of the Championships were held at a single venue. European Athletics released the full and final startlists on 16 June 2023, one week before the event. The previous Super League was expanded to sixteen teams and renamed the First Division. Italy won the First Division with 426.5 points. For the first time, medals were also awarded for individual performances across all three divisions, as part of the 2023 European Games.[1][2][3]

European Athletics Team Championships Format

Format

The winner of each individual discipline and each relay shall score 16 points, the second will score one fewer, and so on. National teams, athletes or relay teams with no valid performance, disqualified or not finishing shall not score. If two or more athletes tie for a place in any event, the attributable points shall be divided equally between them. The team having the highest aggregate number of points shall be the winner of the championship, and win both the gold medal and the Championship trophy.[4] After the conclusion of the athletics program of the European Games 2023, the following relegation and promotion was made for the 2025 edition of the European Athletics Team Championships in Madrid, Spain:[5]
  • the three lowest ranked teams of the First Division were relegated to the Second Division.
  • the three highest ranked teams of the Second Division were promoted to the First Division.
Races up to 800 metres, including hurdles events of similar distance, and all relays will be raced in two heats, with the results amalgamated to find a final order in the event. There will be no finals in these events. In races from 1500 metres upwards, one heat of 16 will take part. In field events, vertical jumps (high jump and pole vault) will be divided into two simultaneous groups (A and B), while horizontal events (long jump, triple jump, and throws) will have all athletes compete together. Both heats and groups will be seeded so that the highest ranked athletes compete together, with the exception of the relays, which will be seeded by overall standings one hour before the event.[6]
